[1] Observations by T. Jacob John
Date: Sat 13 Aug 2016
From: T Jacob John <tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in> [edited]


re: Poliomyelitis update (11): Nigeria (BO) 20160811.4410331.

Very special thanks to ProMED-mail for bringing out, on 11 Aug 2016, 1st in international circles, the disturbing news of wild poliovirus type 1 (WPV-1) circulation and 2 polio cases detected in Nigeria, where we believed it had been eliminated.

I have an important observation to make. When WPV-1 was detected in sewage in parts of Israel, in 2013, the "blame" was on the lack of intestinal immunity induction by IPV [inactivated polio vaccine]. In Nigeria, 3 healthy children, contacts of cases, had WPV-1 infection detected through stool testing. Their OPV [oral polio vaccine] history was 10, 8 and 6 doses -- most probably partly trivalent OPV and partly bivalent OPV (with types 1 and 3, giving much higher vaccine efficacy for type 1).

It is in the nature of poliovirus infection that one gets repeated infections in spite of immunity due to IPV, OPV or even natural wild virus infection. In 1982 there was a nationwide WPV-1 outbreak in Taiwan, during which well-vaccinated children appeared to have participated in virus circulation.

However, the duration of virus shedding and quantum per gram of stool, would vary, inversely proportional to immunity level, irrespective of whether induced by infection or by IPV.

It must be noted, however, that no child has (reportedly) developed polio paralysis after taking 3 doses of IPV. As the moderator has rightly pointed out, vaccine efficacy of OPV has wide variations across geography.

We hope the affected region in Nigeria will be accessible to high coverage of vaccination, with both bivalent OPV (in campaigns) and with IPV (in EPI [the Expanded Programme on Immunizations]).

--
T Jacob John
Retired Professor of Clinical Virology, from Christian Medical College
439 Civil Supplies Godown Lane, Kamalakshipuram
Vellore, Tamil Nadu, 632002
India
<tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in>

[ProMED-mail would like to thank Professor T Jacob John for his valuable observations on polio vaccinations and challenges. Dr T Jacob John is one of the leading authorities on polio and polio vaccines in the world. Dr John's observation that there have been no reported cases of paralytic polio in a child with a history of having received 3 doses of IPV is an important observation. There was extensive spread of the wild poliovirus (WPV1) in Israel with positive environmental samples going from the south to the north of the country, without a single case of paralytic disease identified in the country (see prior ProMED posts below), where IPV has been the vaccine in use for many years. The advantage of OPV is also its disadvantage -- the spreading of the vaccine virus in the community so those unvaccinated individuals may be vaccinated by children vaccinated in the community. As the attenuated vaccine virus in the OPV has been associated with vaccine associated paralytic disease, and has reverted to increased neurovirulence producing the circulating vaccine derived polioviruses (cVDPVs) which have led to cases of paralytic disease, the IPV is now being introduced as part of the polio eradication endgame to eliminate cVDPVs as well. - Mod.MPP]

